              <inheritsPopupMenu value="false"/>
              <selectedTextColor color="-16711423"/>
              <text value="GENERAL❗:&#10;- HexOust is a two-player game on a base-7 hexagonal board ⬡&#10;- Each player has a colored stone assigned (red 🔴 or blue 🔵)&#10;&#10;GOAL ✅:&#10;- Clearing the board from all your opponent's stones by capturing them&#10;- Draws are NOT possible ❌&#10;&#10;&#10;HOW TO PLAY THIS GAME 💻:&#10;- The board starts out empty&#10;- The red player plays first 🔴&#10;- A player places a stone on the board, in a valid cell:&#10;&#9;- If the player made an NCP then it will become the opponent player’s turn&#10;&#9;- If the player made an CP then it will stay their turn until a NCP is made or no more valid placements are available&#10;&#9;- The first player that eliminates all opponent's groups wins 🏆&#10;&#10;STONE'S PLACEMENTS 📍:&#10;- Non-capturing placement (NCP):&#10;&#9;1. Forms no connections (adjacencies) with any stones&#10;&#9;2. Forms one or more connections only with enemy stones&#10;&#9;3. Does NOT form any connections with stones of its own color&#10;- Capturing placement (CP):&#10;&#9;A player places a stone which forms one or more connections with their own stones (creates a new, larger group)&#10;&#9;The new group must have one or more connections with the opponent’s groups upon its creation AND all opponent’s groups must be smaller than the new group&#10;&#9;Upon making such a placement, all opponent’s groups with connections with the placed stone are removed from the board&#10;- Invalid placement ❌:&#10;&#9; Sometimes a placement migth not be valid, the game is going to warn you&#10;- Winning placement 🏆:&#10;&#9;If a player places a stone that eliminates all the opponent's stones, then they win the match&#10;&#10;TURNS 🔄:&#10;- A player concludes their turn by making a non-capturing placement&#10;- After a capturing placement, a player will continue their turn until they make a non-capturing placement&#10;  Therefore, a player can make multiple placements per turn and can potentially clean up all the opponent’s groups" noi18n="true"/>
